⁣
Skin infections are a really common chief complaint in urgent care. I’ve seen anything from sepsis due to a cat bite, necrotizing fasciitis, to your typical abscesses & cellulitis. It is important to know which bacteria are associated with each infection, as your antibiotics must cover for the suspected bacteria⁣
⁣
Check out my weekly blog (link in bio)—in partnership with HippoEd’s Urgent Care bootcamp, where I give you a summary on a couple of their amazing lectures on skin infections/animal/human bites & appropriate antibiotics. ⁣
⁣
Be sure to give @hippoeducation a follow for more! ⁣
⁣
Key notes: ⁣
🔸do not confuse stasis dermatitis with cellulitis⁣
🔹Cellulitis is most commonly caused by: streptococci⁣
🔸Cat bites have a higher tendency to become infected⁣
🔹Time to onset of infection for dog bites: 24 hours⁣
🔸Time to onset of infection for cat bites: 12 hours⁣
🔹important bacteriology for cat/dog bites: Pasteurella (along with mixed flora)⁣
🔹Laceration over a knuckle is considered a fight bite until proven otherwise—there is a really good legal case on UC rap about this!⁣
🔸Important bacteriology for human bites: Eikenella (along with mixed flora)⁣
🔹Bounce-backs for skin infections often occur due to incorrect antibiotic coverage or presence of abscess that must be drained⁣
🔸Be sure to know when to transfer a patient to higher level of care—more on this on the blog⁣
⁣
